## Universal Security Items

### 1. Authentication & Authorization

- [ ] All endpoints require appropriate authentication
- [ ] Authorization checks enforce least-privilege access
- [ ] No endpoints accidentally exposed without auth
- [ ] Session/token management follows best practices

<!-- PROJECT-SPECIFIC EXAMPLE:
For projects using OAuth 2.0 / OIDC:
- [ ] OAuth scopes are correctly validated
- [ ] Token refresh uses secure rotation
- [ ] PKCE is enabled for public clients

For projects using API keys:
- [ ] API keys are not logged or exposed in responses
- [ ] Rate limiting is enforced per key
- [ ] Key rotation mechanism exists
-->

### 2. Input Validation

- [ ] All user inputs are validated and sanitized
- [ ] SQL/NoSQL queries use parameterized statements
- [ ] File uploads are validated (type, size, content)
- [ ] URL/path inputs are validated to prevent traversal attacks

<!-- PROJECT-SPECIFIC EXAMPLE:
For projects using ORMs (SQLAlchemy, Prisma, etc.):
- [ ] Raw queries are avoided; ORM methods used instead
- [ ] Any raw queries use parameterized inputs

For projects with GraphQL:
- [ ] Query depth limiting is configured
- [ ] Input types are strictly defined
- [ ] Introspection is disabled in production

For projects with SPARQL or other query languages:
- [ ] Query injection prevention measures in place
- [ ] User inputs never concatenated into queries
-->

### 3. Data Exposure Prevention

- [ ] No sensitive data in log output (passwords, tokens, PII)
- [ ] API responses don't leak internal data (stack traces, DB schemas)
- [ ] Error messages are generic for external users, detailed for internal logs
- [ ] Sensitive fields are masked in any debugging output

<!-- PROJECT-SPECIFIC EXAMPLE:
For projects handling PII:
- [ ] PII is encrypted at rest
- [ ] PII access is audit-logged
- [ ] Data retention policies are enforced

For projects with payment data:
- [ ] PCI DSS requirements are met
- [ ] Card data is never stored in plain text
-->

### 4. Infrastructure Isolation

- [ ] Internal services are not exposed to public networks
- [ ] Database ports are not publicly accessible
- [ ] Admin interfaces require VPN or IP allowlist
- [ ] Environment variables don't contain secrets in CI logs

<!-- PROJECT-SPECIFIC EXAMPLE:
For containerized projects (Docker/K8s):
- [ ] Container images use non-root users
- [ ] Network policies restrict pod-to-pod communication
- [ ] Secrets are managed via secret stores (not env vars)

For serverless projects:
- [ ] Function permissions follow least-privilege IAM policies
- [ ] API Gateway has proper throttling configured
-->

### 5. Dependency Vulnerabilities

- [ ] No known critical CVEs in direct dependencies
- [ ] Dependency lock files are committed and up to date
- [ ] Automated vulnerability scanning is configured in CI
- [ ] Any CVE exceptions are documented with rationale

<!-- PROJECT-SPECIFIC EXAMPLE:
For Node.js projects:
- [ ] `npm audit` reports no critical vulnerabilities
- [ ] `package-lock.json` is committed

For Python projects:
- [ ] `pip audit` or `safety check` reports clean
- [ ] `requirements.txt` or `poetry.lock` is committed

For Go projects:
- [ ] `govulncheck` reports no issues
- [ ] `go.sum` is committed
-->

